snippet.textDisplay:
My uncle had a Pontiac Trans-Sport, it was one of the 4,271 Trans-Sports that were sold in The Netherlands in the 90's.
It was a bizarre looking car for the time, Especially in Europe. there was not much like it, Maybe the old Renault Espace, the Toyota Previa didn't sell well here. Many family's still had stationwagons.

Later in the 90's early 00's there was an invasion with Chrysler Voyagers and grand Voyagers. Both the early Voyagers and the Trans-sports are getting really rare here. Not many are left!

snippet.textDisplay: There was 25 minutes of my life I will never get back. I have a 1995 Silhouette (exactly like the one Travolta drove in "Get Shorty") and have owned it for almost 14 years. Granted, it's semi-retired after we got our Aztek but she will fire up and go anywhere she wants. Other than a few ECMs and fuel pumps, she has been super reliable with one of the best engines ever made, the venerable L27 3.8 V6 and the so-so 4T60E which we did have to have rebuilt because these vans produce an insane amount of underhood heat so after the trans was rebuilt, we added the largest trans cooler that would fit. Before temps on the highway were 225-230F; after the cooler they are 160-170F in town. My husband added 16" wheels from a Cutlass Supreme with wider tires, plus a rear sway bar and it handles as well as a 4th gen Camaro - as I pissed off a Z28 owner keeping up with him in some twisties once. The only things I hate about the van are there are more blind spots than a house and the steering wheel is roughly 3/4-1" to the right of the driver's seat. If the old L27 ever dies, we are going to build an L67 supercharged 3800 for it. What I love, on a trip to Dallas and back with 5 people and luggage, we averaged 30 MPGs.
snippet.textOriginal: There was 25 minutes of my life I will never get back. I have a 1995 Silhouette (exactly like the one Travolta drove in "Get Shorty") and have owned it for almost 14 years. Granted, it's semi-retired after we got our Aztek but she will fire up and go anywhere she wants. Other than a few ECMs and fuel pumps, she has been super reliable with one of the best engines ever made, the venerable L27 3.8 V6 and the so-so 4T60E which we did have to have rebuilt because these vans produce an insane amount of underhood heat so after the trans was rebuilt, we added the largest trans cooler that would fit. Before temps on the highway were 225-230F; after the cooler they are 160-170F in town. My husband added 16" wheels from a Cutlass Supreme with wider tires, plus a rear sway bar and it handles as well as a 4th gen Camaro - as I pissed off a Z28 owner keeping up with him in some twisties once. The only things I hate about the van are there are more blind spots than a house and the steering wheel is roughly 3/4-1" to the right of the driver's seat. If the old L27 ever dies, we are going to build an L67 supercharged 3800 for it. What I love, on a trip to Dallas and back with 5 people and luggage, we averaged 30 MPGs.

snippet.textDisplay: I love these older vehicle reviews you do, they're unique and fun to watch and not just information like all the reviews of modern models. I seem to remember a family friend of ours having a Pontiac Transport when I was a kid, I remember the "Dustbuster" styling. I also remember a commercial for one showing the automatic sliding door. The Silhouette/Transport wasn't the only minivan to have a single sliding door, my parents always had GMC Safaris when I was growing up and they only had one sliding door. They also had the door windows that were vents too and the seats you had to remove. I remember a cowboy commercial for the Pontiac Montana showcasing it's eight person seating.

snippet.textDisplay: 13:35 what are you talking about? Everyone knows that the safest restrain system was your mothers arm, which she alway flung towards you whenever she had to stop abruptly. Of course, that also meant that whoever in the back was in a car seat was flung forward, and possibly even upside down, because there was no LATCH system, and the seat belt did not want to lock itself whenever you actually needed it to. Which is why booster seats were for ages 4 years and younger. 5yos were just safer on a regular seat back then.
